<section style="padding:0 24px;">
  <div style="max-width:860px;margin:0 auto 56px;">
    <h2 class="section-heading" style="font-size:clamp(22px,3vw,32px);margin:0 0 18px;">Egress code compliance for Crete rental properties</h2>
    <div class="rich"><p>Crete's rental market runs on two groups: Doane University students looking for affordable off-campus housing and workers tied to the local plants and businesses that anchor the town's economy. Both groups fill basement bedrooms, and Nebraska rental code doesn't allow a basement room to be advertised or used as a bedroom unless it has a code-sized egress window.</p><p>We see this most often in older Crete houses that were divided into rentals decades ago, long before egress requirements were enforced the way they are now. A basement window that's too small, painted shut, or blocked by an undersized well won't pass a rental inspection, and it puts tenants at real risk if there's ever a fire.</p><p>Our <a href="/egress-window-installation-lincoln/">egress window installation</a> process is the same whether the home is owner-occupied or a rental: we cut the opening to meet minimum width, height, and net clear opening requirements, then finish with a well sized to match. Landlords get a written estimate up front, so there's no surprise when it's time to close on financing or list a unit.</p></div>
  </div>
</section>
<section style="padding:0 24px;">
  <div style="max-width:860px;margin:0 auto 56px;">
    <h2 class="section-heading" style="font-size:clamp(22px,3vw,32px);margin:0 0 18px;">Working with Crete's older housing stock</h2>
    <div class="rich"><p>A good number of Crete homes near downtown and along the older residential streets date back to the early and mid-1900s, built when basement windows were meant for light and ventilation, not emergency exit. Foundations from that era often have narrow window openings set high in the wall, which makes a straight window swap impossible without enlarging the opening itself.</p><p>That kind of work means cutting concrete or block, which is a bigger job than a standard <a href="/basement-window-replacement-lincoln/">basement window replacement</a>, but it's what actually gets an old opening up to code instead of just installing a slightly bigger window that still falls short. We size every cut to the specific egress window going in, not a generic template, since older Crete foundations rarely match modern standard dimensions exactly.</p><p>If your home still has its original basement windows, we can tell you during a free estimate whether an enlargement is needed or whether a straight <a href="/egress-window-replacement-lincoln/">egress window replacement</a> will clear code as-is.</p></div>
  </div>
</section>
<section style="padding:0 24px;">
  <div style="max-width:860px;margin:0 auto 56px;">
    <h2 class="section-heading" style="font-size:clamp(22px,3vw,32px);margin:0 0 18px;">Serving Crete and Saline County</h2>
    <div class="rich"><p>Crete is the Saline County seat, and we work throughout town and the surrounding rural properties, not just inside city limits. That includes acreages and farmhouses outside Crete proper where basement bedrooms are just as common as they are in town, and where window well drainage matters even more given the flatter, slower-draining ground typical of the area.</p><p>We're based out of Lincoln and make the drive down Highway 33 regularly, so scheduling a Crete job doesn't mean a longer wait than a job inside Lincoln. See typical project pricing on our <a href="/egress-window-cost/">egress window cost</a> page, or compare notes with our work in nearby <a href="/egress-windows-seward/">Seward</a> and <a href="/egress-windows-beatrice/">Beatrice</a>.</p><p>Whether it's one egress window for a single rental bedroom or a full basement finish with two or three windows, we give the same free written estimate and licensed, insured install on every Crete job.</p></div>
  </div>
</section>
<section style="padding:72px 24px;background:#EAF5FB;">
  <div style="max-width:860px;margin:0 auto;">
    <span class="kicker">FAQ</span>
    <h2 class="section-heading" style="font-size:clamp(24px,3.5vw,36px);margin:0 0 32px;">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
    <div style="display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:16px;">
      <div style="background:#fff;border:1px solid #e3ded4;border-radius:8px;padding:24px 28px;">
        <h3 style="font-family:'Nunito Sans',sans-serif;font-size:18px;font-weight:800;color:#0A3D5C;margin:0 0 10px;">Do Doane University rental houses in Crete need egress windows?</h3>
        <p style="font-size:15px;line-height:1.75;color:#555;margin:0;">If a basement room in a Crete rental is used or advertised as a bedroom, it needs a code-compliant egress window regardless of who's renting it. This applies to houses near campus that landlords have converted for student housing just as much as long-term family rentals. We install and size the window to meet the net clear opening Nebraska code requires.</p>
      </div>
      <div style="background:#fff;border:1px solid #e3ded4;border-radius:8px;padding:24px 28px;">
        <h3 style="font-family:'Nunito Sans',sans-serif;font-size:18px;font-weight:800;color:#0A3D5C;margin:0 0 10px;">How much does egress window installation cost in Crete?</h3>
        <p style="font-size:15px;line-height:1.75;color:#555;margin:0;">Pricing in Crete runs similar to our Lincoln jobs, generally in the range covered on our egress window cost page, since the biggest cost driver is whether we're cutting a brand-new opening or replacing an existing window. Older Crete foundations that need the opening enlarged for code compliance run toward the higher end. We give an exact number after seeing the basement in person, free of charge.</p>
      </div>
      <div style="background:#fff;border:1px solid #e3ded4;border-radius:8px;padding:24px 28px;">
        <h3 style="font-family:'Nunito Sans',sans-serif;font-size:18px;font-weight:800;color:#0A3D5C;margin:0 0 10px;">Does Crete's clay soil affect window well drainage?</h3>
        <p style="font-size:15px;line-height:1.75;color:#555;margin:0;">Yes. Like much of southeast Nebraska, the soil around Crete drains slowly, so a window well without a proper gravel base and drainage path can fill with standing water after heavy rain. We build every well with compacted gravel below the sill and tie into existing drain tile where it's available, which matters more on flat lots near the Big Blue River.</p>
      </div>
      <div style="background:#fff;border:1px solid #e3ded4;border-radius:8px;padding:24px 28px;">
        <h3 style="font-family:'Nunito Sans',sans-serif;font-size:18px;font-weight:800;color:#0A3D5C;margin:0 0 10px;">How far is Crete from your Lincoln office?</h3>
        <p style="font-size:15px;line-height:1.75;color:#555;margin:0;">Crete is about 25 miles southwest of Lincoln, roughly a 30 to 35 minute drive down Highway 33. We schedule Crete jobs on the same timeline as work inside Lincoln, so distance doesn't mean a longer wait for an estimate or install.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>
